In this weekly address, President Obama discusses his efforts to build a fairer and more equitable criminal justice system. He highlights the Department of Justice's designation of the week of April 24-30 as National Reentry Week, during which the Administration will focus on strong reentry programs that can make communities safer. The President announces additional steps to ensure that applicants with a criminal history have a fair chance when competing for a federal job. The White House will also call on businesses to commit to hiring individuals who have served their time, and will issue a report on the economic costs of high incarceration rates. The President emphasizes that reforming the criminal justice system is not just about practicality and economics, but also about upholding the ideals of the nation. He calls for bipartisan support in Congress for a criminal justice reform bill.